body:
Thanks for taking the time to report this.

This code works on other simulators, but fails to verilate
```
module top;
    initial begin
        typedef byte unsigned byte_q_t[$];
        byte_q_t data;
        data = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
        $display("data: %p", data);
        data = data[3:$];
        $display("data: %p", data);
    end
endmodule
```
The error is:
```
%Error-UNSUPPORTED: queue_typedef.sv:8:23: Unsupported/illegal unbounded ('$') in this context.
                                         : ... note: In instance 'top'
    8 |         data = data[3:$];
      |                       ^
                    ... For error description see https://verilator.org/warn/UNSUPPORTED?v=5.036
%Error: Exiting due to 1 error(s)
```
If I remove the typedef then it works as expected:
```
module top;
    initial begin
        byte unsigned data[$];
        data = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
        $display("data: %p", data);
        data = data[3:$];
        $display("data: %p", data);
    end
endmodule

```
output:
```
data: '{'h1, 'h2, 'h3, 'h4, 'h5} 
data: '{'h4, 'h5} 
```
The typedef should work, and it's necessary because you can't declare a function that returns a queue, or define an array of queues without a typedef.  I have seen other problems when using typedefs, but this is the first one I have narrowed down to this small of an example.

What 'verilator' command line do we use to run your example?
```
verilator -j $(nproc) -o foo --binary queue_typedef.sv && obj_dir/foo
```
What 'verilator --version' are you using?
```
Verilator 5.036 2025-04-27 rev v5.036
```
Did you try it with the git master version?  No

What OS and distribution are you using?  Tested on both archlinux and Rocky Linux 9.6

May we assist you in trying to fix this in Verilator yourself?  Yes, if you'd like

